		<h4 id="project_one">Project One</h4>
		<h5>Landscape Research Group</h5>

		<div class="grid_12">
			<div class="image"><%= image_tag('p01_01.jpg') %></div>
		</div>


		<p>
		The content of the Creative Landscapes workshop series was tested in 2014 through a project entitled the <i>Landscape Research Group.</i>
		</p>

		<p>
		The <i>Landscape Research Group</i> was open to UK-based students who fell into one of two categories: Level 3 Extended Dip., Foundation Dip., or A’Level students with a place on a BA (Hons) Graphic Design course commencing September 2014, or, Level 4 BA (Hons) Graphic Design students progressing onto Level 5 September 2014. 
		</p>

		<p>
		A call for participants was publicised via a network Higher Education tutors. 29 students from the following institutions applied: 
		Aquinas College, Arts University Bournemouth, University of Brighton, University of Chester, University of Huddersfield, London College of Communication, Sheffield Hallam University, Staffordshire University and University Centre Stockport College. 
		</p>

		<p>
		Fifteen students were selected based on the premise of working with a minimum of one from each applicant institution.
		</p>

		<p>
		The LRG participants worked on five briefs in total. Each brief had to be completed within one week. Participants were encouraged to spend a maximum of two hours on each brief with the aim of encouraging ‘knee-jerk’ responses. In addition, the briefs were intentionally ‘open’, so as to encourage the participants to make their own 
		decisions about how to proceed, as opposed to providing prescribed output methods. The research methods of the participants were later quantitatively and qualitatively analysed.
		</p>

		<p>
		The <i>Landscape Research Group</i> sought to address two key research objectives:<br/>
		1. To analyse the dominance and effect of digital technology/the Internet on undergraduate graphic design student work and the design process.<br/>
		2. To explore undergraduate graphic design research methodologies in relation to the linear/non-linear exploration of the landscape of the design process.
		</p>

		<p>
		The results of the <i>Landscape Research Group</i> informed the content of the Creative Landscape workshop series.
		</p>

