		<h4 id="project_two">Project Two
		<h5>Creative Landscapes: Grasmere &amp; Rydal Water, 2015</h5>

		<div class="grid_12">
			<div class="image"><%= image_tag('p02_01.jpg') %></div>
		</div>
		<!-- [FILM TBC] -->

		<p>
		In October 2015, the Creative Landscapes workshop series successfully ran with a cohort of 45 first year BA (Hons) Graphic Design and BA (Hons) Illustration students from Staffordshire University. 
		</p>

		<p>
		The group collaborated with Debbie Wigglesworth, of The Paper Library, where they learnt about paper manufacturers from around the world, before travelling to the Lake District for a tour of James Cropper paper mill in Kendal. 
		</p>

		<p>
		Whilst on the trip, the students were asked to document the landscapes of Grasmere and Rydal Water according to their 5 senses, later producing a print-based publication each. Photography was not allowed, and paper had to play a key role to play in the communication of their ideas. James Cropper kindly sponsored the student work by supplying several paper stocks for them to work with. 
		</p>

		<p>
		The student work produced was of an exemplary standard. A selection of the work will be on display at the Brewery Arts Centre in Kendal until early September 2016.
		</p>


		<p>
		After taking part in the Creative Landscapes workshop series, the students said:
		</p>

		<p>
		“There is merit in the detour.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“I have learnt how to observe and allow my senses (not just my sight) to
		enhance my work.”
		</p> 

		<p>
		“I’ve learnt that creative projects aren’t just about the visual, but also about what you
		think. I’ve learned think creatively.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“I have become much more experimental, rather than doing things for a 
		pre-determined, literal way.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“I am now more open minded about the possibilities of visual communication.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“The project opened my mind to not just think about the final product but instead
		work through a more thorough, organic process.”
		</p>
		 
		<p>
		“I learnt to inspect things more closely.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“For an idea to be found, first you must be lost.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“I learnt a lot about observation and using all of my senses to communicate through
		visual language.”
		</p>

		<p>
		“I have begun to re-think how I work, and have realised the value of a well-informed
		and considered design process.”
		</p>

